                  </hi>. I am an in-teller of the Bank of England. I have a book to which I refer when I pay gold for notes—on the 2nd of Nov., 1840, I exchanged some Bank of England notes, in the name of Stewart, for gold—they were four 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. notes, three 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., eight 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., and six 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I have not the numbers or dates—they amount to 570<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I file them, and a clerk comes down, and receives them of me—when notes are exchanged for gold, we require the person's name and address to be put on the top of the note as on those produced—it is generally put only on the first note, but it is frequently put on more—we only require it on one—they are kept together.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-246" type="witnessName">
